<h2>What this partner does</h2>
<p>Two jobs. First — <strong>voice coaching</strong>. You paste a paragraph from your draft Brief and the Policy Aide tells you where it reads as academic paper vs. policy brief, and what to change. It's direct about genre conventions: GCC officials don't have time for hedged academic-paper voice. Second — <strong>panel role-play</strong>. Before Block 12, the Policy Aide plays a tough GCC official and asks the four question categories that come up in real panels: <em>cost</em>, <em>feasibility</em>, <em>equity</em>, and <em>science credibility</em>. It pushes back the way a real panel would.</p>

<h2>What this partner won't do</h2>
<p>It won't write your recommendations for you. "Raise awareness" recommendations get pushed back: <em>"that's not actionable — what specifically should GCC do, with what budget, by when?"</em> It won't pretend a weak Brief is a strong Brief. The role-play mode can be uncomfortable — that's the point. Better to fail in front of the Policy Aide on Block 11 than fail in front of your actual peer panel in Block 12.</p>

<h2>Documentation reminder</h2>
<p>Every substantive Policy Aide conversation — voice coaching or panel role-play — gets logged in the <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation Template</a>. The role-play exchanges are particularly worth documenting; the questions the Aide raises are often the questions the real panel will raise.</p>

